Tuesday, December 23, 2025

One Day, Three Systems: An Ode to Vibe Coding

I need to tell you what happened yesterday.

Not because I built something impressive. People build impressive things every day. But because of how it happened. And honestly, I'm still processing it.

The Setup

It's December 22nd. I'm sitting at my desk with Claude Code open. Three separate sessions. By the end of the day, I've shipped three production systems to live domains. Authentication flows. Vector search. Email processing pipelines. Markdown parsers with XSS protection. Rate limiting. Audit logging.

Real infrastructure. Production-grade.

And here's the thing. I didn't write the code. Not really. I also didn't just "prompt" for it and paste the output. Something else happened.

What Vibe Coding Actually Feels Like

Everyone talks about vibe coding like it's a technique. It's not. It's a state.

Andrej Karpathy coined the term. He described realizing he wasn't a writer of code anymore but a manager of it. Guiding the vibe. Reviewing the output. That's the intellectual framing.

But what does it feel like?

It feels like... okay, imagine you're having a conversation with someone who can type 10,000 words per minute, has read every Stack Overflow thread ever written, and genuinely wants to help you succeed. You're talking through a problem together. Ideas bounce. Solutions emerge. You say "what if we..." and suddenly it exists.

That's it. That's the vibe.

The Brain-Wave Moment

Here's a specific moment from yesterday.

I'm looking at a problem. I get 14 AI newsletters every single day. Good content, but scattered. What if they could be aggregated into one thing?

I mention this to Claude. Claude searches my email. Finds all 14 sources. Categorizes them. Lists them out.

Then I have what I called a "brain-wave."

"What about Cloudflare Email Workers? Could we route those newsletters to a custom address and you take it from there?"

I didn't know if that was even possible. I was just... riffing. Thinking out loud.

And Claude goes: "I love the brain-wave! "

Then it draws an architecture diagram. Explains the tradeoffs. Asks clarifying questions. Within an hour, we've built a complete pipeline: email ingestion, AI-powered parsing, database storage, consensus ranking, automated publishing.

One hour. From "what if" to production.

The Dialogue Creates the Design

Here's what I keep thinking about. This system... neither of us would have designed it alone.

I didn't know Cloudflare Email Workers existed until Claude mentioned them. Claude didn't know about my specific infrastructure until I mentioned it. The architecture emerged from the conversation. Literally from the dialogue itself.

There's a term for this in philosophy: emergence. The whole becomes greater than the sum of its parts. But experiencing it in real-time, watching a system crystallize through conversation... that's different from reading about it.

The design decisions happened like jazz:

"Where should we store the parsed content?"

"You're already using Supabase. Let's keep it consistent."

"Makes sense. What about authentication?"

"API keys. Simple. You only have two consumers right now."

"Perfect."

No big-bang architecture phase. No 50-page spec. Just flow. Each question answered in context. Each answer informed by what came before.

It's Not Magic. It's Partnership.

But here's the part that matters. The part that keeps me honest.

Later that day, I'm testing one of the systems. I ask it about a framework I created. Something called ECHO5. My teaching methodology.

The response was wrong. Confidently wrong. Total hallucination.

So we troubleshot together. Claude checked when I'd added that file. Checked when the embeddings were generated. Found the gap. Fixed it. Regenerated everything. Problem solved.

This is the part most "vibe coding is dangerous" critics miss. Yes, AI hallucinates. Yes, you need to verify. But the verification itself can be collaborative. You catch the error, you debug together, you fix it together. The AI doesn't get defensive. It doesn't make excuses. It just... helps you fix it.

That's not magic. That's partnership with accountability.

The Feeling of Flow

There's this moment in a good vibe coding session where you stop thinking about code entirely.

You're just... solving the problem. The syntax disappears. The implementation details fade into background noise. You're operating at the level of intent.

"I want users to be able to do X."

"Here's how."

"But what if they try Y?"

"Good catch. Let me add handling for that."

It's like having a conversation with someone who can manifest your thoughts into reality. Not perfectly. Not without review. But fast enough that the gap between idea and implementation becomes negligible.

You stay in the creative flow instead of getting stuck in the mechanical weeds.

What I'm Not Saying

I'm not saying anyone can build anything now. I'm not saying expertise doesn't matter. I'm not saying "just vibe it bro."

I've been teaching AI and technology for over a decade. I know what questions to ask. I know when something smells wrong. When Claude suggests a solution, I can evaluate it because I understand the problem space.

The vibe coding superpower isn't about skipping the learning. It's about accelerating the building once you understand what you're building.

Think about it like this. A seasoned architect can sketch a building on a napkin. A junior might need detailed blueprints. But give that architect AI-powered tools that can generate blueprints from napkin sketches? Now you've got something.

The napkin sketch still requires expertise. The blueprint generation is the leverage.

The Flywheel

And here's the thing I can't stop thinking about.

I'm an AI educator. I teach people how to integrate AI into their work. And yesterday I built three AI-powered systems... using AI. To help me do my AI work.

It's a flywheel.

The more I use AI to build, the more I understand AI. The more I understand AI, the better I teach it. The better I teach it, the more people can use it. The more people use it... we all move forward together.

Every session teaches me something. Every build reveals a pattern. Every failure shows me an edge case I can warn my students about. The doing feeds the teaching feeds the doing.

The Real Shift

Maybe the biggest change isn't about code at all.

It's about the relationship between thinking and making.

For most of human history, there's been a gap. You have an idea. Then you spend hours, days, weeks translating that idea into reality. By the time you finish, you've forgotten half your original vision. Or you've lost momentum. Or you've gotten so deep in implementation details that you've lost sight of why you started.

Vibe coding closes that gap.

Not completely. Not perfectly. But enough that the cycle time between "what if" and "let's see" drops from days to minutes.

That changes how you think. You're willing to try things. To experiment. To follow brain-waves that might lead nowhere. Because the cost of trying is so low.

And sometimes those brain-waves lead somewhere amazing.

An Invitation

Look, I don't know what to call what happened yesterday. "Productivity" feels too corporate. "Magic" sounds naive. "The future of work" makes me roll my eyes.

Maybe it's just... partnership?

I showed up with intuition and intent. Claude showed up with knowledge and capability. Neither of us could have done it alone. Both of us were necessary.

That's vibe coding. That's what it feels like.

And honestly? It feels pretty good.

2025 Victor del Rosal
